EUROPEAN ENERGY REPORT via NewsNet
January 5, 1996

EVN SUCCESS IN HUNGARY

Among Austrian bidders for a share in Hungary's gas privatisation (EER
449/12), only regional utility EVN managed a successful offer.

Jointly with Germany's Bayernwerk, EVN now holds 50% plus one share in
Koegaz, a regional gas utility serving about 190,000 customers in a
southwestern region encircling Lake Balaton and extending to the
Slovenian and Croatian borders. The consortium joint investment amounts
to $67m, up $20m from its first bid.

EVN will have few immediate gains from the deal; the service territory
does not border on Austria, as would have been the case had EVN gained
a hold in other Hungarian gas utilities for which it had bid.

Nevertheless, EVN's success is unlikely to induce much pleasure with
Austria's state-controlled gas monopoly, OMV, which failed in its
Hungarian bids.

EVN's deal further strengthens its ties with the German utility, with
which it shares major stakes in Austria's private gas and oil producer
RAG. OMV and the 51% state-owned electricity authority Verbund have
felt themselves threatened by Bayernwerk, which has made offers on
several Austrian privatisations.



