<A NAME = "18"></A>Copyright
EUROPEAN ENERGY REPORT via NewsNet
January 5, 1996

GERMAN IMPORTERS PREDICT 10% SLUMP IN 1996 SALES

The German coal importers federation says it expects coal sales to
suffer a decline of 10% in 1996.

Purchases of fresh coal are expected to be postponed as major consumers
use up the "comfortable" coal stocks which were accumulated during the
'Jahrhundert' contract, which expired at the end of 1995. Sales of both
German and imported coal are expected to be affected to the same
degree.

It is all the more ironic that import coal prices will probably remain
at their current low level during 1996, assuming no significant shifts
in currency rates take place - "proof of the continuing value for money
of imported coal", stresses the importers' association.

In the first 10 months of 1995, imported steam coal prices averaged
DM76/t ($53/t) hard coal equivalent (hce), while German steam coal cost
virtually four times as much at DM291/t hce before subsidies took
effect.



