<A NAME = "15"></A>Copyright
PLATT'S OILGRAM PRICE REPORT via NewsNet
January 2, 1996   Vol. 74, No

US WEST COAST: PRICES SLIP INTO '96

   The end of 1995 approached quietly in Los Angeles with little talk heard
for most products. Los Angeles unleaded languished at the previous day's
level of 57.00-58.00 cts with few buyers seen. Talk was mostly notional
with some narrower ranges heard.
   Traders said it appeared the Portland unleaded market was starting to
slide a little faster. The range dipped to 54.25-55.25 cts as the market
continued to "figure things out" following the reopening of the pipeline
from Seattle.
   Bay unleaded was said to be losing ground to Los Angeles and talked at
least 1.50 cts lower than Los Angeles. Oxy was reported done at 2.50 cts
over Bay unleaded. Reformulated talk was no higher than 2.00 cts over Los
Angeles conventional unleaded.
   Jet fuel prices in Los Angeles appeared closer to the 66.25 cts level at
which the last reported deal was done. Apparently little was getting done,
but there continued to be enough outside pressure in the form of refinery
problems and Asian prices to keep jet supported.
   A CARB seller in Los Angeles was reportedly looking for 67.00 cts early
while the Bay was pegged around 62.50 cts. Low sulfur No. 2 oil held steady
through the day at 60.00-61.25 cts with 60.00 cts reported done in Los
Angeles for the back half of the month. Portland L/S No.2 oil talked lower
at 57.75-58.75 cts.
   Demand into the fuel oil market screeched to a halt on the last trading
day of the year. Traders scrambled to supply what was left of the demand in
the bunker market.
   In Los Angeles, sources reported that bunker-C sold at $111.50,
resulting in a slight increase in the price of 380 CST and 180 CST.

Copyright 1996 The McGraw-Hill Companies



